with fascinating images not widely known in the west, the volume demonstrates the significance of visuality in understanding the protean nature of this powerful worldwide revolutionary movement. Contributions address regions as diverse as Singapore, Madrid, Lima and Maputo, moving beyond stereotypes and misconceptions of Mao Zedong Thought's influence on art to deliver a survey of the social and political contexts of this international phenomenon. At the same time, the book attends to the the similarities and differences between each case study. It demonstrates that the chameleonic appearances of global Maoism deserve a more prominent place in the art history of both the twentieth and twenty-first centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunism and artzChina. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aArt history.  aArt.  aCultural Revolution.  aGlobal Maoism.  aMao.  aMaoism.  aPolitical art.  aPropaganda.  aSixties.1 aAntoine, Elodie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBigotte Vieira, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBories, Estelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaiter, Colette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalimberti, Jacopo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalimberti, Jacopo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeng, Yan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraber, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuiné, Anouk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandsberger, Stefan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongoni, Ana, 